=========================================
std::unique_ptr (C++11) - INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

Q: What is unique_ptr?
A: unique_ptr is a smart pointer that provides exclusive ownership of a dynamically allocated object 
and automatically deletes it when it goes out of scope.

Q: Why is copy not allowed?
A: Copying is not allowed because unique_ptr enforces exclusive ownership, and multiple owners 
could cause double deletion.

Q: Why is move allowed?
A: Move semantics transfer ownership from one unique_ptr to another while maintaining a single owner.

Q: get() vs release()?
A: get() returns the raw pointer without releasing ownership, whereas release() returns the raw pointer 
and relinquishes ownership.

Q: What does reset() do?
A: reset() deletes the currently managed object and optionally takes ownership of a new object.

Q: What is make_unique()?
A: make_unique() is the preferred, exception-safe way to create a unique_ptr without explicitly using new.

Q: unique_ptr vs shared_ptr?
A: unique_ptr has a single owner and no reference counting, while shared_ptr allows multiple owners using reference counting.

Q: What is RAII?
A: RAII is a C++ technique that ties resource lifetime to object lifetime, ensuring automatic cleanup through destructors.
